Note: if you want to print this same key chain out, you might want to raise the size to 200%. even though most of the features came out very sharp and clear, depending on your printer, some areas might not be clear or even get skipped over. This specifically helps for the letters because they did come out nice; however their was some stringing around the inner parts of the letters.

We were able to print out the reference photo we had chosen and then followed a sketch plan while measuring each individual puzzle piece at there sides and cut curves. we then marked down the measurements used them to build it on Solidworks.

We used this image we found through google images in order to replicate it and embellish off of it with the letter R, make extrusions,some varied singular pieces and the little letters on the side, spelling our last name.

As a class, after learning how to use CAD, are next assignment was to build a 2-d extruded object of anything (school appropriate). When got into partnerships, we had think something we would want to design and my partner and I came up with the simple puzzle pieces board  figure after seeing a puzzle pics chess board idea on Thingaverse. We able to find a reference photo and make the figure, adding the key chain aspect to it when we were printing it out.
My partner and I had made a sketch plan on Google docs for step by step instructions on how to make the puzzle piece from the picture to a extruded 2-D model.

title: Linear Advance Bridging Test
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Hello Makers,

this test is for printers that have the linear advance function in their firmware, or just want to test some bridging.

If you never heard about linear advance, look at Matt´s Hub. Great explanation as always.

https://mattshub.com/2017/10/02/linear-advance/

I made this test, cause i knew with the new linear advance function for Prusa i3 MK2S, the printer could handle double the print speeds for PLA e.g.

So that means 120 mm/s for the print head with standard PLA, and the material is too sluggish to "fall down" when going over gaps.

But what bridge distances are possible? Thats what the part is for.

Starts with a 10mm long bridge (see green line for dimensions) and ends with 35mm on the small part and 60mm on the large one. The bridges get longer by 5mm increments per bridge.

This test will also show how sluggish your material behaves.

Have fun with testing your new linear advance, i love that function.

Hi all,

This is something that about everyone can build. Just a fun little project I have been wanting to do for my Rostock Max V3.

The Base:
Basically, I made a frame comprised of 2"x4"s which measures 2ft by 2ft. Then cut a piece of scrap plywood to that same measurement and screwed it down on top. I then added legs, 2ft long each.

The Enclosure:
I purchased these 2'x4'x 1/8" polycarbonate at a local glass shop. I have 4-2'x4' panels for the sides and 1-2'x2' panel for the top. I bought some 1"x4"x8' pine for the corners. I ended up ripping these boards in half to reduce weight and I realized there wasn't really a need for them being the original size. Then since polycarbonate will not crack upon drilling, I drilled all holes followed by screws. This is probably the most crucial step in making the enclosure besides measurements. You do not want your wood to split.

This is work in progress, so I will be updating this with my further additions. I plan to make a functioning door with some hinges I will print and maybe even implementing some kind of heating system.

Update: 10/30/17
Noise reducing foam is on its way to my address, I purchased it off of ebay for pretty cheap compared to other kinds you can get. I will do a noise test and see if it makes any difference, I'm banking on it :) If anything, it will also help retain the heat inside of the enclosure by sealing the edges where it contacts the base.

Update: 1/29/18
I noticed the stepper motors and the circuit boards were pretty warm with the whole enclosure heats up, so I wanted to get some outside cooler air into the top of the printer where are the essentials are. So this is what I came up with, its a 120mm pc fan tied into a 12v wall adapter.

title: Pitch-roll head & mounting collars for linear actuator

description.text:
I designed these for a robot project (https://hackaday.io/project/20153-robot-7-undefinable-wheeledlegged-dev-platform). They fit the linear actuators common on eBay and similar. They may be useful to someone...

They fit a 70mm hole (I have a hole-saw this size), secured with 6 screws or bolts. The bottom collar takes a 47mm OD bearing up to ~20mm thickness. I used an old headstock bearing from my motorbike that has an ID of ~20mm, enough to take the bottom mount of the actuator. There are slots for M4 nuts, allowing M4 screws to snug-up against the body of the actuator.

The pitch-roll head is a bracket for standard size servos that push-fits on to the shaft of the actuator (20mm) allowing a platform to be kept level (or not!).

The main reason for building this was due to the fact that the MFJ-269 does not have a way to hang it on something while using it. As such, I've modeled in a small hole in the back of the case so that one can thread a hook into the case. One can also thread an eye into it and attach a carabiner to the eye for securely hanging the unit.
The longest surface in this object is 225mm. If this poses a problem for some, I can upload a version without the carrying handle that is only 175mm at your request.
Make sure your printer can handle small bridges well before printing, as the hexagonal fill will surely task it's ability to do so. As such, this model should not require any support.
2017/10/19 updated with a slight modification due to finding one surface that would have needed a support to be printed.

Then, simply remove the screws on the side holding the back cover in place, put the cover and the analyzer into this case, and utilizing the original screws, fasten the whole assembly together.

description.text:
The tolerances are a bit tight for some glass sizes and print settings on the original version, so I updated those with the version 2 files.

Bed clamps for 200x200mm to 230x200mm 4mm thick glass on 220x220mm 3.3mm thick heated beds. Print two each of A and B orientations to get pieces for four corners.

Screw guide for 230x200mm glass:

  • 4x 15mm or longer M3 screws (16..18mm is optimal)
  • 4x 10mm or longer M3 screws (6..8mm is optimal)

Screw guide for 220x200mm glass (print the 230x200mm model):

  • 8x 15mm or longer M3 screws (16..18mm is optimal)

Screw guide for 210x200mm glass (print the 230x200mm model):

  • 8x 15mm or longer M3 screws

Screw guide for 200x200mm glass:

  • 8x 15mm or longer M3 screws (16..18mm is optimal)

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Print as solid as possible, no supports and in the orientation of the STL. Don't use PLA, because it'll soften and warp in use. ABS, PETG and such should be fine. For best results, print with thick enough perimeters and top/bottom layers to make the model solid.

For best results, drill the mount holes of the clamps clean with a 3mm drill and heat-set M3 nuts in the recession for them. Clean up the screw inset hole if the screw head doesn't fit right away.

Drill the adjustment screw holes of the clamps clean with a 2.5mm drill bit and use an M3 tap to thread them.

Insert the M3 adjustment screws into the tapped holes, but not deep enough to get all the way through.

Remove the corner screws of the bed either one at a time while it's mounted in the printer or all at once if you want to remove the bed.

Slide the parts over the corners of the bed, either with the glass removed or in place.

Insert the bed adjustment / mounting screws into the mounting holes and insert the adjustment nuts and springs while you do so, where applicable.

If you don't want to re-level your bed, take a caliper measurement of the distance of the bed and the carriage in each corner before mounting the clamps. If your caliper has a locking screw, use that as well and your caliper can act like a height jig.

Finally, seat the glass so that it floats free and is level to the bed. Then carefully tighten the adjustment screws until the glass is securely in place, but not tight enough to break it.

Ok, here it is. Dumbed down a bit, removed the motor, because its really much more fun to spin it yourself, and then you dont have to go get one too. Makes it cheaper. And it spins very well as is, so im content.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yFNyQ6QBHLI

And these were a hit at our party. Easily the best costumes there. Granted, there were only like 6 other people that dressed up.

Will upload better pics tomorrow (hopefully) after wrapping the box.

Ive included a 'inner clamp no motor' file, which is the inner piece without the motor mount part.

Print stuff as you see fit. Belt clip is designed to be printed flat as you'd expect, the hinging long portion to be printed horizontally across your bed, standing up (with support, of course)
Everything else is pretty self explanatory.
I printed the outer bearing race at 0.5% larger in the x/y direction, as its a bit tight as is, but youll probably need to test it depending on your printer.

After printing and assembly, remove the hinge part from the belt clip and heat that sucker up right in the middle with a heat gun. Youll need to bend this to suit you, depending on how large your... package... is. See image for how much i bent mine and feel free to compare size.

Hopefully thats everything, let me know if i missed something.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aAEwIUMloC0

As part of a joke for a friends wedding, all the groomsmen are lip syncing dick in a box... as a result, we need some boxes attached to our belts. Now, you could go low tech and just strap them on, but we have the technology, not only to make them spin, but to make them spin on their own!

Assembly instructions are fairly simple,

  1. Cut a hole in a box
  2. Put your junk in that box
  3. Make her open the box
    **and assemble the rig and wire it all up with some batteries and switch

Anyway, making this one for halloween as a test, hopefully it ends up good and i can make whole set.

WIP, motors are on their way, so gearing might change in the future. Currently set to use 100 RPM, with a 4:1 ring/pinion reduction, resulting in 25 rpm (i think i mathed right). But may change motor speed, or gear reduction. Might even put in a planetary set just for fun.

Uses 6mm airsoft BBs for a bearing, so youll need roughly 50 of those.

When motors are finally here, and i have the parts printed (hopefully the motors are as i think they will be), ill hopefully post some pics/videos. But for now, enjoy the music... https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m3d-BkxL-9I

description.text:
Huge Star Wars fan here! Loved working on this. I found some "official" prop dimensions online and used those for this assembly, so it should be very accurate. The only things that people might have an issue with this design is that it doesn't include the ring that's supposed to hook onto the bottom (mainly because I'd rather get an actual metal one that won't break) and also none of the buttons or switches actually move. Other than that, it should be very accurate to the actual thing. Enjoy!

Things you should know:
This assembly consists of 9 parts. I recommend printing parts 2, 3, 4, and 6 normally, and print parts 1, 5, 7, and 8 upside-down. Part 3.5 should be positioned with the flattest surface on the bed of the printer and the buttons facing upward. Only parts 2, 3.5, and 6 will require support material. Any amount of infill should be fine. Refer to the image to see how each part attaches to which. I suggest using a very strong adhesive to attach each part (I suggest an epoxy). I printed mine on an Ultimaker 2+ with a 0.4 mm nozzle and an infill of 15%. Total, it took me a little over 24 hours to print (I'll add this info to the download file).

  • Sorry, the one I made isn't all the same color because I ran out of silver colored PLA. However, I still plan on sanding, priming, painting, gluing, and adding a protective layer to it. I'll post those pictures once I've done so.

description.text:
Update: I have added in an adapter with a non-adjustable front sight(will need supports). I have reduced the size of the section that is cut out to help keep the front sight horizontal.
You just need a adjustable rear sight. I happened to have a CR600W adjustable rear sight. I'll be sure to design a adjustable rear sight based on almost all the same dimensions as the CR600W rear sight:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2618419

I've made an adapter out of a adapter that allows a 2240/1377 silencer adapter to be used with the PP700W Air Pistol.
The 2240 silencer adapter can hold the silencer fairly tightly unlike printed threads that will simply snap off. You will have to cut off some excess of the 2240's adapter (just before the grub screw holes). Where you cut will determine how far in the printed portion covers the shroud. Then the 2240 adapter simply slots into the printed portion of the adapter (you may have to reduce the diameter of the 2240 adapter). Use a silencer or a muzzle break to seat the 2240 adapter in place. The whole adapter then slides over the shroud. No grub screws are needed as it is relatively tight.

I recommend that it is printed in ABS at 0.2mm nozzle for a perfect fit.

Also if your silencer is off lightly sand the face of the printed portion. It will help if you epoxy the threaded portion to the printed portion to keep the angle consistent.

author: Brebs

description.text:
A replacement for the centre main frame of a Walkera Ladybird.  
My first Ladybird receiver stopped working (It would not bind, and this seems to be a common problem). After disassembling the Ladybird, I found my main frame had cracked, and I did not like the way the receiver pcb was a structural member of the frame. My belief is that a dry joint has formed on the pcb due to the flexing/stresses of being run into things etc.  
So I designed a new frame with the intention of having the PCB isolated from any loads.  
Marked as WIP as I may change the design to more securely fit the PCB.

Should be printed on it's side, should be orientated correctly in the file.  
I recommend putting an AA battery through the centre hole as the arms are a tight fit, and if you slip it will cut the motor wires. The AA battery acts as a convenient stop, and you can make sure that all the arms are pushed in an equal distance.  
I am currently just sticking the board down with a 4 tiny pieces of sticky back foam (as seen in the picture). although this is problematic as I find I tear the foam off as I unplug the battery.

I made this adapter to use 120 mm fans with a 280 mm radiator. I recently upgraded my PC case to a Fractal Design Meshify C and quickly realized that I couldn't mount my 280 mm AIO radiator in the front of the case with the GPU that I have. I then found out that the case doesn't officially support mounting a 280 mm radiator in the top due to clearance issues with the RAM & VRM heatsink. This adapter offsets the fans towards the glass side of the case in order to clear those things. The only difference I've noticed with using 120 mm fans, instead of the 140 mm, is that they're slightly more audible, but that could just be due to the case being more open than my old Define R4. Other than that, I seem to be getting the same thermal performance.

Here's my Imgur album about them: https://imgur.com/a/LCJCA

When I printed them, I printed the 140 mm w/ duct part first, then I printed the 120 mm part, after which I just super glued them together. I am including the non-split .stl though, just in case anyone wants to try and mess around with printing it.

Also, I noticed that the model looks like it's missing faces when I imported it into Simplfy3D, but it turns out fine when you render the gcode. IDK what the deal is there.
